{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox person |name = Artur de Sacadura Freire Cabral |image = ArturDeSacaduraFreireCabral1.jpg |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1881|5|23}} |birth_place = [[Celorico da Beira]], [[Portugal]] |disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|1924|11|15|1881|2|23}} |disappeared_place = [[North Sea|Northern Sea]] |occupation = Portuguese Navy officer |father = Artur de Sacadura Freire Cabral|mother=Maria Augusta da Silva Esteves de Vasconcelos |known_for = First aerial crossing of the South Atlantic }}
'''Artur de Sacadura Freire Cabral''', [[Order of the Tower and Sword|GCTE]] (23 May 1881 &ndash; 15 November 1924), known simply as '''Sacadura Cabral''' ({{IPA-pt|sɐkɐˈduɾɐ kɐˈbɾaɫ}}), was a Portuguese [[aviation]] pioneer who in 1922, together with [[Gago Coutinho]] (1869–1959), conducted [[first aerial crossing of the South Atlantic|the first flight across the South Atlantic Ocean]], and also the first using astronomical navigation only, from [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]], to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]. On 15 November 1924, he [[List of aerial disappearances|disappeared while flying]] over the [[English Channel]], along with his co-pilot, Mechanical Corporal José Correia, due to fog and his shortening eyesight (which never kept him from flying). Although some mechanical wreckage from his seaplane had been discovered four days later, the bodies were never recovered. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vidaslusofonas.pt/sacadura_cabral2.htm |title=Sacadura Cabral Pioneer Airman |accessdate=16 February 2012 |last=Sodré |first=João |publisher=Vidas Lusophonus |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815031249/http://www.vidaslusofonas.pt/sacadura_cabral2.htm |archivedate=15 August 2012 }}</ref> A statue dedicated to them is located in Lisbon. Another statue is located in his hometown, Celorico da Beira. He was the granduncle of Portuguese politicians [[Miguel Portas]] and [[Paulo Portas]].
